Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` and use the `Shell.Navigation` API:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Returning true cancels the hardware/software back
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // cancel the default navigation
    }
}
```

> `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the **Android hardware back button** and the **Shell back arrow**. Return `true` to cancel navigation, then conditionally navigate with `GoToAsync("..")`.

**3. Replace the back arrow with a "Cancel" button**

In your XAML, hide the default back button and add a toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            IsVisible="True"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>
</ContentPage>
```

Or set it inline:

```xml
<Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                        Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
```

Then in your view model (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        return;
    }

    bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
        "Unsaved Changes",
        "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
        "Discard", "Stay");

    if (leave)
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnBackButtonPressed`** — handles Android HW back + shell back arrow; return `true` to block.
- **`BackButtonBehavior`** — replaces the arrow with custom text/icon and routes taps to your command (also suppresses the default `OnBackButtonPressed` path, so put your logic in the command).
- **`GoToAsync("..")`** — the Shell-idiomatic way to go back one page.

Since `BackButtonBehavior.Command` takes over the back button tap, your unsaved-changes guard only needs to live in `CancelCommand` for the toolbar button, plus `OnBackButtonPressed` for the Android hardware back button.
